      <h1>How to Calculate Percentages: 5 Methods for Everyday Math</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">Percentages show up everywhere — on receipts, in spreadsheets, on nutrition labels, and in news headlines. Once you understand what a percentage actually means and learn a few reliable methods, you can handle any percentage problem without reaching for a calculator.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <TableOfContents />

    <h2>What Does "Percent" Actually Mean?</h2>
    <p>The word "percent" comes from the Latin <em>per centum</em>, meaning "per hundred." When you see 25%, it literally means 25 out of every 100. That is the entire concept: a percentage is a way of expressing a number as a fraction of 100.</p>
    <p>This is why 50% means half (50 out of 100), 100% means the whole thing, and 200% means double. Keeping this "parts per hundred" idea in your head makes every method below easier to understand.</p>

    <h2>Method 1: The Basic Percentage Formula</h2>
    <p>The most fundamental percentage calculation answers the question: <em>"What percentage is this part of the whole?"</em></p>
    <p><strong>Formula: (Part &divide; Whole) &times; 100 = Percentage</strong></p>

    <h3>Example: Calculating a Test Score</h3>
    <p>You answered 42 questions correctly out of 50.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Divide the part by the whole: 42 &divide; 50 = 0.84</li>
      <li>Multiply by 100: 0.84 &times; 100 = <strong>84%</strong></li>
    </ol>
    <p>This works for anything — grades, completion rates, survey results, or batting averages.</p>

    <h2>Method 2: Finding a Percentage of a Number</h2>
    <p>This answers the question: <em>"What is X% of Y?"</em> You use this when calculating tips, discounts, and taxes.</p>
    <p><strong>Formula: Number &times; (Percentage &divide; 100) = Result</strong></p>

    <h3>Example: Calculating a 20% Tip</h3>
    <p>Your restaurant bill is $65.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Convert the percentage to a decimal: 20 &divide; 100 = 0.20</li>
      <li>Multiply: $65 &times; 0.20 = <strong>$13.00 tip</strong></li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Example: Finding a Sale Price</h3>
    <p>A $120 jacket is marked 30% off.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Find the discount amount: $120 &times; 0.30 = $36</li>
      <li>Subtract from the original: $120 &minus; $36 = <strong>$84 sale price</strong></li>
    </ol>
    <p>Shortcut: you can also multiply by 0.70 directly (since 100% &minus; 30% = 70%). $120 &times; 0.70 = $84.</p>

    <h2>Method 3: Percentage Change</h2>
    <p>This tells you how much something increased or decreased relative to its original value. You see this in finance, budgets, and performance tracking.</p>
    <p><strong>Formula: ((New Value &minus; Old Value) &divide; Old Value) &times; 100 = % Change</strong></p>

    <h3>Example: Rent Increase</h3>
    <p>Your rent went from $1,400 to $1,540 per month.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Find the difference: $1,540 &minus; $1,400 = $140</li>
      <li>Divide by the original: $140 &divide; $1,400 = 0.10</li>
      <li>Multiply by 100: 0.10 &times; 100 = <strong>10% increase</strong></li>
    </ol>
    <p>A negative result means a decrease. If your rent dropped from $1,400 to $1,260, the change would be &minus;10%.</p>

    <h2>Method 4: Mental Math Shortcuts</h2>
    <p>You do not always need a formula. These shortcuts let you estimate percentages in your head within seconds.</p>

    <h3>The Building Blocks</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>10%</strong> — Move the decimal point one place left. 10% of $85 = $8.50.</li>
      <li><strong>1%</strong> — Move the decimal point two places left. 1% of $85 = $0.85.</li>
      <li><strong>5%</strong> — Find 10%, then take half. 5% of $85 = $4.25.</li>
      <li><strong>20%</strong> — Find 10%, then double it. 20% of $85 = $17.00.</li>
      <li><strong>25%</strong> — Divide by 4. 25% of $85 = $21.25.</li>
      <li><strong>50%</strong> — Divide by 2. 50% of $85 = $42.50.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Combining Building Blocks</h3>
    <p>You can build any percentage from these pieces:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>15%</strong> = 10% + 5%. For $85: $8.50 + $4.25 = $12.75.</li>
      <li><strong>18%</strong> = 20% &minus; 2%. For $85: $17.00 &minus; $1.70 = $15.30.</li>
      <li><strong>33%</strong> &approx; divide by 3. For $85: roughly $28.33.</li>
      <li><strong>75%</strong> = 50% + 25%. For $85: $42.50 + $21.25 = $63.75.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>This approach is fast enough for tipping, estimating discounts in a store, or checking whether a sale is actually a good deal.</p>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-mid" format="horizontal" />

    <h2>Method 5: Using Proportions</h2>
    <p>The proportion method works well when the other methods feel awkward, or when you need to find an unknown in a word problem.</p>
    <p><strong>Set up two equal fractions and cross-multiply:</strong></p>
    <p>Part / Whole = Percent / 100</p>

    <h3>Example: "12 Is What Percent of 80?"</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Set up: 12 / 80 = x / 100</li>
      <li>Cross-multiply: 12 &times; 100 = 80 &times; x &rarr; 1,200 = 80x</li>
      <li>Solve: x = 1,200 &divide; 80 = <strong>15%</strong></li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Example: "What Is 35% of 200?"</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Set up: x / 200 = 35 / 100</li>
      <li>Cross-multiply: x &times; 100 = 200 &times; 35 &rarr; 100x = 7,000</li>
      <li>Solve: x = 7,000 &divide; 100 = <strong>70</strong></li>
    </ol>
    <p>Proportions are especially useful for students, because they work the same way regardless of whether you are solving for the part, the whole, or the percentage itself.</p>

    <h2>Common Real-World Percentage Problems</h2>

    <h3>Sales Tax</h3>
    <p>Your state has 8.25% sales tax and you are buying a $250 item. Multiply: $250 &times; 0.0825 = $20.63 in tax. Total: $270.63.</p>

    <h3>Grade Calculation</h3>
    <p>Your syllabus weights homework at 30%, midterm at 30%, and final at 40%. You scored 92 on homework, 85 on the midterm, and 78 on the final. Weighted average: (92 &times; 0.30) + (85 &times; 0.30) + (78 &times; 0.40) = 27.6 + 25.5 + 31.2 = <strong>84.3</strong>.</p>

    <h3>Discount Stacking</h3>
    <p>A store offers 20% off, and you have a 10% coupon. These do not add up to 30%. The first discount brings a $100 item to $80. The second takes 10% off $80, giving you $72 — a total discount of 28%, not 30%.</p>

    <h2>Common Percentage Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Confusing percentage points with percentages.</strong> If interest rates rise from 3% to 5%, that is a 2 percentage-point increase but a 66.7% increase relative to the original rate.</li>
      <li><strong>Applying percentage change in reverse.</strong> A 50% drop followed by a 50% gain does not get you back to the original. $100 &rarr; $50 (down 50%) &rarr; $75 (up 50%). You are still down 25%.</li>
      <li><strong>Stacking discounts by addition.</strong> As shown above, consecutive percentage discounts multiply, they do not add.</li>
      <li><strong>Dividing by the wrong number in percentage change.</strong> Always divide by the <em>original</em> value, not the new one.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Wrapping Up</h2>
    <p>Every percentage problem boils down to the same relationship: part, whole, and rate. Once you recognize which two you have, you can find the third with any of these five methods. For quick estimates, the mental math shortcuts are all you need. For precision, use the formulas — or let a calculator handle it.</p>

